{"source_key":"sha256-0a53d184cd6345dd0adae2529d73d2f3","record_index":312,"record_hash":"sha256:28a6391e553cca1212d216ac0f160e2fbd29508b7d78a64a2859b64d48310e52","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:28.560Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Findings:\\n\\n- [P1] [environment.rs:463](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:463) makes `TomlRefMetadata::iter()` empty. That breaks GitButler TOML metadata discovery: `head_info()` relies on metadata iteration to discover workspace/stacks when `HEAD` is not the workspace ref. The cleanup removed the side effect, good, but also dropped the legacy projection behavior. Result: GitButler repos can degrade to plain-Git observations and miss stack/review/branch metadata. Mirror legacy `VirtualBranchesTomlMetadata::iter()` in a read-only way.\\n\\n- [P2] [environment.rs:180](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:180) can return `partial` when worktree capture fails and workspace capture succeeds with no stacks/targets. Spec says `failed` means no useful environment observation was collected. Add an emptiness check before calling that `partial`.\\n\\n- [P2] Tests cover “no synthetic change ids” for plain Git, but not positive stored change-id projection or TOML metadata projection. The missing TOML test is why the `iter()` regression slipped through.\\n\\nTargeted checks run:\\n`cargo test -p but-agentlog capture_turn_stores --quiet`\\n`cargo test -p but-agentlog environment_from_parts --quiet`\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:28.560Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}